    "recap_headline": "Georgia Southern University",
    "recap_text": "STATESBORO \u2014\nThe Georgia Southern baseball team (5-17, 0-5 SBC) were defeated by Marshall (13-8, 5-0 SBC) by a score of 13-5 on Saturday afternoon (March 21st) at J.I.\nHOW IT HAPPENED:\nAfter a calm opening frame, the Herd started their scoring in a powerful way as Oliver Service launched a solo homer to give Marshall a 1-0 lead.\nSouthern came right back swinging in their second inning after three singles and a fielder's choice ended up plating both\nBrady Christman\nand\nBennett Edwards\n.\nMarshall would end up taking the lead for good in their third after three singles, walk, hit batter and a costly catcher's balk with the bases loaded to make the score 5-2, a lead that Marshall would not look back on.\nIn the fourth, a triple from Halter set up another run for Marshall to increase their lead to four.\nIn the fifth, two more\u00a0runs were added on by the Marshall bats before their defense would hold strong and leave Southern to strand the bases loaded in the bottom of the frame with only a\nBryson Trammell\nsac-fly to show for it.\nThe next two chances at the plate for Marshall saw them up their lead to 13-3, their largest of the day, and threaten to end the game early.\nHowever, Christman would put a hold on that as he belted his first career home run to right-center to make it a 13-4 contest.\nIn the ninth, the Eagles still fought valiantly as Edwards himself homer over the Blue Monster in right, but would ultimately not be enough as the Eagles fell via two strikeouts to close the game.\nNOTES:\nAlex Mason\nmade his first collegiate start on the day. He would start the game strong, striking out two of the first five batters he faced.\nTwo freshmen led the team in hits as both Christman and Edwards each collected a trio of them on the day.\nFor Christman, it would also be his first multi-hit game of his career.\nFrank Wells\nhad his first career extra base hit with a double down the left field line.\nOf the 11 hits on the afternoon for the Eagles, eight of them came from freshmen.\nUP NEXT:\nThe Eagles and Thundering Herd close out their series tomorrow afternoon (March 22nd), with first pitch set for 1 PM at J.I. Clements Stadium for a day of Good 'Ol Fashioned Baseball.",
